<font color="#FF0000">VISITING THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 23  4:28:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I visited the Wall on a cold, rainy Thursday night.  Some of the lights were out near the Wall, but the names could still be seen.  The rain drops drifted lazily down the names, and, suddenly, I thought tear drops were being shed for all those young men and women who died in a far Asian war.  <br>
     The memories were still visible from the dinner table during the 1960's and 1970's.  War came home to our dinner table every night during those dark days.  I had only 15 minutes at the Wall because of our bus tour.  I wanted to walk slowly and absorb the religion of the moment.  Those young service people gave the people of Southeast Asia something to live for.  I supported the war, yet, many of our colleagues were totally against it.  Not every one on a college campus is a dove.  Those tear drops keep lingering in my mind as our young men and women were blown apart by land mines and booby traps. The gaunt faces of the POWs will always haunt the television screen.  <br>
     I'm glad to have finally had a chance to visit the Wall that meant so much in our modern history.  The Wall will always be there, but the dead cry out for recognition.  A member of my family said to me, after I returned from Washington:  &quot;Did you touch the Wall?&quot;  Maybe it was too sacred a place to touch.  I found my footsteps that cold rainy night hesitating at every set of lighted names.  Perhaps, I tried to thank those brave service people for their sacrifice.  As I left the memorial area, I talked to a Vietnam veteran in a lighted kiosk.  He was selling Vietnam mementoes and POW remembrances.  I thanked him for being out on such a cold night.  The Wall endures.
<p><code>-- jay.christensen@csun.edu  (Dr. G. Jay Christensen) </code><p>


